<p local-id=3D"8ab3a896a3b9">Static analysis handles the majority. Each sub=
sequent layer activates when the previous layers produce sparse or ambiguou=
s results. Confidence scores in the response shape naturally reflect which =
layer produced the link.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"e268f6986d1a" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Openquestions">Open questions</h3>
<ul local-id=3D"ca9caf88-0bc3-486d-80df-140f2bbb36af">
<li local-id=3D"13c512c0-673a-4115-90fa-1672b6da0466">
<p local-id=3D"44f2f645b8b1">Should transitive call-site linkage be include=
d in static analysis, or fully deferred to coverage data?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"86b86c44-0a08-4691-984e-72891935095e">
<p local-id=3D"021246ad0b1d">What confidence score thresholds should separa=
te static-verified links from embedding-derived candidates?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"627ebaa4-b894-4ba5-a810-6a8ebc162568">
<p local-id=3D"f3656415103b">Is dynamic instrumentation worth the engineeri=
ng cost for MVP, or is it a clean post-MVP upgrade?</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"13f6b45c383c"></p>
<hr local-id=3D"cb5fd6bbc9ca">
<h3 local-id=3D"f44cdb44f47f" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-PartB:Cross-CuttingArtefactHandling">Part B: Cross-Cutting Artefact Ha=
ndling</h3>
<p local-id=3D"ecdcf778ab14"><strong>Problem</strong>: A cross-cutting arte=
fact (logger, base class, utility function, shared validation module) is to=
uched by nearly every test in the codebase. Querying the test harness for <=
code>Logger.log</code> might return 200 covering tests, which is worse than=
 useless. This is a signal-to-noise problem at the linkage level, not a cla=
ssification problem.<br><br>
A strength score would partially addresses this: each test would have very =
low strength for a utility artefact. <br>
Strength score:</p>
<blockquote local-id=3D"8733a69f-1871-4a7e-b55d-b42b5bedb4f9">
<p local-id=3D"6a3351e20863"><em>Strength (0.0-1.0) measures how much verif=
ication value a single test provides for a specific artefact. It's derived =
from two signals: <strong>fan-out</strong> (a test covering 3 artefacts has=
 more strength per artefact than one covering 50) and <strong>call-chain di=
stance</strong> (a test that calls the artefact directly has more strength =
than one that reaches it transitively through several intermediate calls). =
A focused unit test targeting the artefact scores high. An e2e test that ha=
ppens to pass through it scores low.</em><br></p>
</blockquote>
<p local-id=3D"d71ee14f90ee">But the sheer volume of results could still ov=
erwhelm an agent's context window and waste tokens.</p>
<p local-id=3D"41b552a17bf5">The <code>tests()</code> primitive applies a m=
inimum strength threshold by default (e.g., <code>strength &gt;=3D 0.3</cod=
e>), filtering out the long tail of incidental coverage.<br>
Agents can override this explicitly (<code>tests(min_strength: 0.0)</code>)=
 when they genuinely need the full picture.<br></p>
<h3 local-id=3D"9204aeba14a2" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Openquestions.1">Open questions</h3>
<ul local-id=3D"71ae0843-fb2f-4ff3-9c46-a01e436fe152">
<li local-id=3D"3a92c2ce-184e-4f37-8e9a-54ca88e01878">
<p local-id=3D"1c2907e843b7">What fan-in threshold reliably identifies cros=
s-cutting artefacts across different codebase sizes?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"f868459f-d2f0-4dca-b361-0857d17484eb">
<p local-id=3D"f26d085d29ba">Should the default strength floor be configura=
ble per-repository?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"c2df130c-8136-4b1f-a4b0-6d854d8dc6c2">
<p local-id=3D"b3ef51958de1">Should cross-cutting detection be automatic on=
ly, or allow user overrides/corrections?</p></li>
</ul>
<hr local-id=3D"58ece1cd8aa7">
<h2 local-id=3D"87bbb22dc71a" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-PartC:TestClassification"><br>
Part C: Test Classification</h2>
<p local-id=3D"1ad6605157ce"><strong>Problem</strong>: Given a test scenari=
o, classify it as unit, integration, e2e, or another type. The classificati=
on appears in the response shape and enables filtering (<code>tests(classif=
ication:"unit")</code>), prioritization (run unit tests first), and signal =
weighting (unit tests have higher strength for their target artefact).</p>
<p local-id=3D"638ffe1b7cef">Test terminology is opinionated and subjective=
. What one team calls a "unit test" another calls a "component test." What =
one team calls "functional" another calls "BDD" or "acceptance." No univers=
al standard exists. Any classification system that imposes rigid definition=
s will conflict with some team's conventions.</p>
<p local-id=3D"f5803b751e4f">Test types differ along two axes:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"8e5f5a8b-5926-4549-bf71-d2a=
1f81ae76c" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr data-local-id=3D"92d1901c-bfe3-4517-8eaf-d5b3bc9c973a">
<th data-local-id=3D"5f57df37-18fe-4d85-9b0e-342b6a3f7246" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"421786390c47">Axis</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"eb29184a-0552-4c8e-aff2-f06556fc152c" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"394709a2f92b">What it captures</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"0b47f5e3-9031-45bf-88b4-1ed80b5c54b5" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"bcc04332fb11">Detectable from coverage?</p></th>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"219ad6d6-8458-4f4d-8588-53eedc5f8df4">
<td data-local-id=3D"d8a54d4a-3a17-4cdf-a449-970fdaba7fcc" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"3d84a7130920"><strong>Coverage shape</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"62764764-d740-4cb0-a1e5-6b85708844bf" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"378456f3b904">What the test touches (fan-out, boundary cross=
ing, depth)</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"51796598-8594-4288-af51-0390d8b55945" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"9197cf362a97">Yes</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"e8362a6d-56ad-463f-a5b9-38123f1e53f2">
<td data-local-id=3D"17e1fc18-9098-426b-81ce-ec933df82bc5" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"38b524c37a2f"><strong>Purpose/intent</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"d135b02a-d2f7-4f9b-b21f-d837e1e5cfec" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"1e9904898fcc">Why the test exists (verifying logic, checking=
 requirements, measuring performance)</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"a458e2d3-c7bd-4eeb-ad73-d62bf0da0de1" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"09de54c41593">No</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p local-id=3D"f8eee6500bb3">Coverage-derived classification can only see t=
he first axis. Distinguishing types that share similar coverage shapes but =
differ in intent (functional vs integration, acceptance vs e2e, smoke vs un=
it) requires metadata or inference beyond coverage.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"26abbf55b961" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Recommendedapproach:Coverage-derivedclassification(primary)+convention=
-basedoverride(secondary)">Recommended approach: Coverage-derived classific=
ation (primary) + convention-based override (secondary)</h3>
<p local-id=3D"8b808ddb62dd"><strong>Primary (MVP): Coverage-derived classi=
fication.</strong> Zero user configuration. Classification is inferred as a=
 derived property from the coverage footprint, specifically artefact fan-ou=
t and service/module boundary crossing:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"0aeb44fc-1cbe-4c41-82c8-f685a9d5738a">
<li local-id=3D"9cfdac2e-76b8-4b86-847f-69457421c020">
<p local-id=3D"59910639ae67">A test covering a single artefact in a single =
file behaves like a <strong>unit test</strong>.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"0087c178-b8e3-4492-b20d-b4e78025aa1d">
<p local-id=3D"8eb034738693">A test touching multiple artefacts across seve=
ral modules behaves like an <strong>integration test</strong>.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"d918e7b9-7a5e-496b-9cad-51f141be737e">
<p local-id=3D"71cb956e847c">A test spanning many artefacts across service =
boundaries behaves like an <strong>e2e test</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"8bdc87925072">This three-tier model captures what coverage d=
ata can actually tell us. Framework-agnostic, language-agnostic, based on a=
ctual behaviour rather than naming conventions. The thresholds (1-3 artefac=
ts =3D unit, 4-10 =3D integration, 11+ =3D e2e) are arbitrary starting poin=
ts requiring empirical validation. If the artefact model includes classifie=
d artefacts (services, module boundaries), these could be leveraged to make=
 boundary-crossing heuristics more robust.</p>
<p local-id=3D"a3ecca3234fb"><strong>Secondary (optional override): Convent=
ion-based classification.</strong> Users who want explicit control configur=
e folder/file naming patterns (e.g., <code>__tests__/unit/</code>, <code>*.=
integration.test.ts</code>). This overrides coverage-derived classification=
 for matching tests.</p>
<p local-id=3D"e77af83880a4">The classification enum is open and extensible=
. Coverage-derived outputs <code>unit</code>, <code>integration</code>, or =
<code>e2e</code>. Convention-based overrides can use any label the user def=
ines, including <code>functional</code>, <code>smoke</code>, <code>acceptan=
ce</code>, <code>performance</code>, or custom types.</p>
<p local-id=3D"193ff6d67b60">The ordering is deliberate: coverage-derived f=
irst means the system works out of the box. Convention-based is available f=
or teams with strong opinions about taxonomy or who need finer-grained dist=
inctions.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"131eeb984bb8" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Alternativeapproaches.1">Alternative approaches</h3>
<p local-id=3D"7c82c249faa6"><strong>Heuristic/rule-based (mock detection p=
er framework)</strong>: Detect framework-specific patterns like <code>jest.=
mock</code>, <code>vi.mock</code>, <code>#[mockall]</code> as signals. Pain=
ful to maintain across frameworks. Deferred for now, may revisit for high-c=
onfidence patterns in supported languages (TS, Rust).</p>
<p local-id=3D"277f6d6bcace"><strong>LLM-based classification</strong>: An =
LLM examines a test's structure, assertions, setup/teardown patterns, and t=
he production code it touches to produce a classification that understands =
<em>intent</em>, not just coverage shape. Could be a local model (Community=
 Edition) or API-based (Enterprise Edition). Potentially more reliable than=
 threshold tuning across diverse codebases. Initially discarded for cost/la=
tency reasons, but the limitations of coverage-derived thresholds weaken th=
e case for thresholds alone. Worth revisiting as an offline enrichment step=
 that shares infrastructure with the intelligence layer (Bullets 4 &amp; 5)=
. Not MVP scope.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"d031d8ce0813" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Openquestions.2">Open questions</h3>
<ul local-id=3D"6d5079d0-2939-4c78-aca0-1063c29a9860">
<li local-id=3D"3f011a0a-4b4b-4a56-9c79-bf316e3f5632">
<p local-id=3D"1f1849ac505e">Are coverage-derived thresholds robust enough =
across diverse codebases, or will frequent misclassification erode trust?</=
p></li>
<li local-id=3D"9879fb15-918e-4b96-82a1-79f2d14cb9e4">
<p local-id=3D"d56649eb82ed">Should the system avoid imposing unit/integrat=
ion/e2e labels entirely and let users define taxonomy from the start?</p></=
li>
<li local-id=3D"03d73095-25f5-4923-bd71-9db5c0591d9d">
<p local-id=3D"83488a30efb2">Should LLM-based classification be reconsidere=
d as a secondary method for cases where coverage shape is ambiguous?</p></l=
i>
<li local-id=3D"1fb663ed-23dd-4d8b-acfe-99f8cc922de6">
<p local-id=3D"7d690d58a13a">What artefact fan-out values define unit vs in=
tegration vs e2e? (D1, requires empirical tuning)</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 local-id=3D"9eca0ff72726" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Limitations">Limitations</h3>
<ul local-id=3D"b037c4f7-67a6-4aec-9fdf-da99e7c23d06">
<li local-id=3D"7f198d84-c010-4646-8eb1-859cd1e80617">
<p local-id=3D"f0e381703e42">Coverage-derived classification can only see c=
overage shape, not intent. Two tests with identical fan-out but different p=
urposes (functional vs integration) are indistinguishable.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"4e8cb651-0159-437d-b292-e074ee760da9">
<p local-id=3D"c511e026ac06">Threshold values are arbitrary and may misclas=
sify in codebases with unusual architecture (deep layering or very flat str=
ucture).</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"1ad510892af2"><br></p>
<p local-id=3D"f8103e8148c8"><strong>Part B: Test classification</strong></=
p>
<p local-id=3D"19dc70014619">This is where the complexity lives.</p>
<p local-id=3D"a861beef988f"><strong>Test terminology is opinionated and su=
bjective.</strong> What one team calls a "unit test" another calls a "compo=
nent test." What one team calls "functional" another calls "BDD" or "accept=
ance." There is no universal standard. Any classification system that impos=
es rigid definitions will conflict with some team's conventions. This is wh=
y the classification enum should be extensible =E2=80=94 coverage-derived p=
rovides a default, users can override with their own labels.<br><br>
One approach: <strong>Coverage-derived thresholds</strong>. A test covering=
 &gt; N artefacts, is considered e2e, <br>
a test covering &lt; M artefacts is considered unit. &gt;M and &lt;N is con=
sidered integration. Quite buggy on its own, could work for some codebases,=
 and be problematic for others.<br>
If we have classified artifacts, such as services, module boundaries, these=
 could be leveraged in such heuristics.</p>
<p local-id=3D"09f3436f3107"><strong>Coverage-derived thresholds are a star=
ting heuristic, not a proven method.</strong> The idea: low fan-out =3D uni=
t, high fan-out =3D e2e. But the thresholds (1=E2=80=933 artefacts =3D unit=
, 4=E2=80=9310 =3D integration, 11+ =3D e2e) are arbitrary starting points =
that need empirical validation. They might work well for some codebases and=
 poorly for others. Projects with a deeply layered architecture might have =
"unit tests" that touch 5 artefacts through a thin abstraction. Projects wi=
th flat architecture might have "integration tests" that only touch 3.</p>
<p local-id=3D"73f2168b1dc8"><strong>The noise problem is real.</strong> A =
cross-cutting artefact =E2=80=94 like a logger, a base class, a utility fun=
ction, or a shared validation module =E2=80=94 will be touched by nearly ev=
ery test in the codebase. If an agent queries the test harness for <code>Lo=
gger.log</code>, it might get back 200 covering tests, which is worse than =
useless. The <code>strength</code> score partially addresses this (each tes=
t would have very low strength for a utility artefact), but the sheer volum=
e could still overwhelm. Possible mitigations: cap the returned results, fi=
lter by strength threshold, or flag cross-cutting artefacts as such and han=
dle them differently. This needs more thought.</p>
<p local-id=3D"1cadad888c99"><strong>LLM-based classification is not ruled =
out.</strong> We initially discarded it because simpler signals exist and t=
he cost/latency tradeoff seemed poor. But the arguments above weaken the ca=
se for coverage-derived thresholds alone. An LLM could look at a test's str=
ucture, assertions, setup/teardown patterns, and the production code it tou=
ches, and produce a classification that understands intent (not just covera=
ge shape). This could be a local model (Community Edition) or API-based (En=
terprise Edition), depending on the product tier strategy. It might actuall=
y be more reliable than threshold tuning, especially across diverse codebas=
es. Worth revisiting as an option rather than a discarded one.</p>
<p local-id=3D"a17dd4c1bd37"><strong>Open questions:</strong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"4131fd3d-47ea-4f0a-adc7-1a5eaf1fc784">
<li local-id=3D"2b6585e0-7d32-4eff-837e-651274aab259">
<p local-id=3D"63b83f74a2ca">Are coverage-derived thresholds robust enough =
across diverse codebases, or will they produce frequent misclassification t=
hat erodes trust?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"b3a99c66-3cb4-42b2-b57d-e87fba718bfc">
<p local-id=3D"0a3c3ce257a5">Should transitive call-site linkage be include=
d in static analysis, or deferred to coverage data?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"6a07de1c-dd85-406d-a1cf-229bdecb7ea2">
<p local-id=3D"e6d7baa6cc60">How should cross-cutting artefacts (utilities,=
 loggers, base classes) be handled to avoid flooding the agent with low-sig=
nal test results?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"b37809b3-a426-4ea4-96c0-607262d7c6de">
<p local-id=3D"9719921897b3">Should LLM-based classification be reconsidere=
d as a secondary method, particularly for cases where coverage shape is amb=
iguous?</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"1d93b01f-86fa-4a23-84e3-f59a0673c0a4">
<p local-id=3D"271297a14d1b">Test terminology is opinionated =E2=80=94 shou=
ld the system avoid imposing unit/integration/e2e labels entirely and inste=
ad let users define their own taxonomy from the start?</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"b8fc368004d7"><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"6d4c0324-4e55-4406-a65d-9e0ae45d9e2c">
<li local-id=3D"40be13ab-3453-45ba-b4a2-fc317ffd26bc">
<p local-id=3D"d857f4c4cf94">Static linkage tells you what a test reaches f=
or, not what it exercises. Direct-only linkage may miss artefacts exercised=
 transitively.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"1bfa6537-3667-4e24-ac1d-fe5ef033f5f1">
<p local-id=3D"a57a2c7db441">Coverage-derived classification can only see c=
overage shape, not intent. Two tests with identical fan-out but different p=
urposes (functional vs integration) are indistinguishable.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"17946838-768d-46e7-8e66-e577289ffce9">
<p local-id=3D"e2ad396bf5f0">Cross-cutting artefacts may produce noisy, low=
-signal results.</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"expander-210433029" class=3D"expand-container">
<div id=3D"expander-control-210433029" class=3D"expand-control">
<span class=3D"expand-control-icon"><img style=3D"vertical-align:middle;" c=
lass=3D"expand-control-image" src=3D"4311d91630dca91c518a4c82359ce683376d58=
bb6226a8b759baf23818de07b7" width=3D"16" height=3D"16"></span><span class=
=3D"expand-control-text">2. Branch/path coverage map and untested paths</sp=
an>
</div>
<div id=3D"expander-content-210433029" class=3D"expand-content">
<p local-id=3D"900b4be5a7d4"><em>Approach:</em> Two data sources combined. =
(1) LCOV coverage reports provide line-level and branch-level execution dat=
a =E2=80=94 which lines were hit, which conditional branches were taken. (2=
) Static analysis (Tree-sitter) of test files creates the structural relati=
onships between test scenarios and production artefacts via import and call=
-site resolution. The LCOV data is then joined against artefact line spans =
to produce per-artefact, per-branch covered/uncovered status =E2=80=94 scop=
ed to the artefact, not the whole file. Each branch lists which tests cover=
 it.</p>
<p local-id=3D"7664779bb94a"><em>Open questions:</em></p>
<ul local-id=3D"2f8bfd1b-4138-414c-b449-3017c7f6c548">
<li local-id=3D"3b114650-1d5a-4b04-83af-7b312f9461e1">
<p local-id=3D"a51f642ab0b4"><strong>When are tests run and coverage genera=
ted?</strong> Options:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"2e366addd86f">
<li local-id=3D"c6c836ca36c8">
<p local-id=3D"a041740f50a9">(a) manually by the developer via CLI,</p></li=
>
<li local-id=3D"a0ef49496274">
<p local-id=3D"869c13c35b66">(b) automatically via commit hook,</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"42ce23de70f8">
<p local-id=3D"7cb8ca5ea089">(c) triggered by the agent before querying. <b=
r></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li local-id=3D"1179ac712a53">
<p local-id=3D"26352d853250">This affects coverage freshness and user frict=
ion. The platform is a local CLI tool, so all options are technically feasi=
ble. The decision impacts workflow integration more than architecture.</p><=
/li>
<li local-id=3D"aedb65e4-953c-4cbf-ab46-978aaa6815e5">
<p local-id=3D"fbc5dd3a8052"><code>verification_level</code> thresholds (D2=
) =E2=80=94 what coverage percentages and test counts define well_tested vs=
 partially_tested vs untested. Requires empirical tuning.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"d35c35320fb0">There's no real alternative to AST-level analy=
sis for knowing where a function starts and ends. Tree-sitter is the right =
tool for this step.</p>
</div>
</div>
<ol start=3D"3" local-id=3D"3608a97f6163">
<li local-id=3D"f2d3d644-3b07-43b0-a1ca-3ad3c522b7b4">
<p local-id=3D"53b258f43744">Assertions and behavioural guarantees inferred=
 from tests</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"058e3583-3b6c-4d78-bf10-7e5d583fe4eb">
<p local-id=3D"6fce6b9f7c00">Required fixtures/factories/mocks for fast ext=
ension</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"b7fe61c8-67ca-4a95-97d2-0bcdba150121">
<p local-id=3D"4589f345a165">Recommended minimal validation suite for a pro=
posed change</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 local-id=3D"73c5a816b234" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-ScopeDecomposition">Scope Decomposition</h3>
<p local-id=3D"72f20b3658b8">These five outputs split into two categories a=
nd three tiers of complexity.</p>
<p local-id=3D"a7f9cd4e03f4"><strong>Category A =E2=80=94 Understanding cur=
rent state (Bullets 1, 2, 3):</strong> What tests exist, what coverage look=
s like, and what behavioural guarantees those tests encode. This is ingesti=
on and linkage work.</p>
<p local-id=3D"6b55abbf6be3"><strong>Category B =E2=80=94 Actionable guidan=
ce (Bullets 4, 5):</strong> What fixtures/mocks are needed to extend testin=
g, and what's the minimal validation suite for a specific change. This is i=
ntelligence/recommendation work.</p>
<p local-id=3D"449d24a23d95">Within Category A, there is a further seam:</p=
>
<ul local-id=3D"93f0576e-8c40-4eea-b3f4-6acc90021f46">
<li local-id=3D"9ec3d917-3788-45c2-ae26-7a52957700ec">
<p local-id=3D"d434c94237f7"><strong>Bullets 1 &amp; 2</strong> are data in=
gestion and linkage problems. The raw inputs are concrete and well-defined =
(test manifests, CI run outcomes, coverage files). The challenge is in the =
join =E2=80=94 stitching line-level coverage data onto semantic artefacts a=
nd keeping it fresh per commit.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"01badad3-2b99-40c2-bc48-3780bd5dd3c5">
<p local-id=3D"aa27ab51df5d"><strong>Bullet 3</strong> is an inference/inte=
lligence problem. Even at its simplest (extracting <code>expect</code>/<cod=
e>assert</code> statements), it requires static analysis of test code. Goin=
g further toward "this test proves X never returns negative values" enters =
LLM-enrichment territory.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"688f42d0f325">Bullets 1 &amp; 2 stand on their own as a soli=
d, useful foundation. An agent or developer can ask "what tests cover this =
function and where are the gaps?" and get a reliable answer purely from dat=
a. Everything else layers on top.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"207b77ce-388e-4850-b1bf-740cf00d03c4">
<h2 local-id=3D"8a0727aa0d73" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.DecisionsMade">3. Decisions Made</h2>
<h3 local-id=3D"d913db052845" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.1Two-StreamIngestionModel">3.1 Two-Stream Ingestion Model</h3>
<p local-id=3D"a490f7682e55">Test-to-artefact linkage is built from two com=
plementary data streams.</p>
<p local-id=3D"bfcfeb6fa323"><strong>Stream 1: Static analysis of test code=
 (structural linkage)</strong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"b1c43dec-2935-4d6e-9cd5-1503a603f618">
<li local-id=3D"adc847c7-c398-4a49-bfa6-8b2a3713ae76">
<p local-id=3D"5385b77b4be0">Parse test files using Tree-sitter =E2=80=94 t=
he same AST parsing infrastructure built for <code>getBlastRadius</code> (e=
xtracting imports, function calls, dependencies). The investment in the sta=
tic analysis pipeline pays off twice.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"9ea42a97-1965-440f-9fe6-0ff07d474838">
<p local-id=3D"db33897d0911">Discover test-specific artefact types that don=
't exist in production code: <strong>test suites</strong> (e.g., <code>desc=
ribe</code> blocks in Jest/Vitest, <code>mod tests</code> in Rust) and <str=
ong>test scenarios</strong> (individual <code>it</code>/<code>test</code> c=
ases, <code>#[test]</code> functions). These are first-class artefacts in t=
he test domain =E2=80=94 the entities that coverage data, classification me=
tadata, and run outcomes attach to.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"bffbe34d-108f-403a-a87a-4ad4070bc967">
<p local-id=3D"44d84000bc7f">Extract which production artefacts a test impo=
rts, calls, or instantiates.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"8cfaaa00-7743-4c0d-8ebb-122994b92cf6">
<p local-id=3D"713d7e576e67">Produces an immediate, always-available mappin=
g: test =E2=86=92 artefact references.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"751ab496-ff0e-4d79-bc16-8c65948298f5">
<p local-id=3D"7a5b21991c70">Available at commit time, costs nothing beyond=
 parsing, works even if CI hasn't run.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"3ce6b8b7-43e5-418a-a2ff-9194cca947fb">
<p local-id=3D"1fb880aee793">Limitation: tells you what a test <em>reaches =
for</em>, not necessarily what it <em>exercises</em>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"5c403c2db517"><strong>Stream 2: CI/coverage report ingestion=
 (execution-verified linkage)</strong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"591d1498-3f88-4771-adb7-c4e98a8cdabe">
<li local-id=3D"2f514bb2-da00-47dd-aa77-52300c83d53d">
<p local-id=3D"8fc6927681ec">Ingest actual execution data =E2=80=94 which l=
ines, branches, and paths were hit during real test runs.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"a03d4e8e-5afc-48a4-9dfb-8b25e499b76e">
<p local-id=3D"f0413fa63357">Coverage reports (e.g., LCOV) provide file + l=
ine-level granularity.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"94a836ae-93c2-439b-9f28-0cb29bd2a1f2">
<p local-id=3D"fbec20e48009">Join against the artefact model (which knows t=
hat <code>UserRepository.findById</code> spans lines 42=E2=80=9367 of <code=
>UserRepository.ts</code>) to produce artefact-level coverage.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"df746bde-4de1-4b07-b86b-82dd1c809b34">
<p local-id=3D"51aaaa064077">This is the ground truth for "what's actually =
tested."</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"a41bfc47-ac29-4e1c-9f18-7e6217a6832d">
<p local-id=3D"bf65b179169d">Limitation: Test coverage needs to run, so we =
can extract results. Can=E2=80=99t be done statically. <br><span class=3D"i=
nline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"76767d05-1d24-4c49-a948-ad190c513e6a">(Ei=
ther by user, via git hook, or some other way, and it=E2=80=99s time consum=
ing)</span></p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"9ab1a678801f"><strong>The two layers together:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"84=
03c3c7-0601-4940-8b8c-a6d76ede93ba" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr data-local-id=3D"20393705-a372-46f1-bf46-50a2e855d019">
<th data-local-id=3D"f62a8122-cfe6-48d4-87e5-ca6bcad7fc5c" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"98217f7bd5ec">Layer</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"8c971af1-f9fd-4086-9450-20f34fd9839d" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"c320891bd35d">Source</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"86d6bba0-0a3a-453f-929e-b894af0b0470" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"9a4bd14bdbbb">Availability</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"31b2ae7f-577b-4b8c-b4e1-be0a915d8715" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"031486b3d998">Precision</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"f32f394f-b942-4284-b862-f3d05c3eed4d" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"9c660eacd2e4">Cost</p></th>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"593d77c1-0593-468a-aa32-324e7d367127">
<td data-local-id=3D"e62b70e9-973b-4073-b452-360ae2fcbdab" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"b305e0739f22">Static</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"91ff919d-c856-46e2-a04d-a7d7866f229d" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"d11141c68f4a">Tree-sitter parse of test files</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"90d7e89f-05ca-4e30-9a58-157464e9a994" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"af844b11b228">Immediate (commit time)</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"4e7ffd2b-eaae-4a19-8e62-52f96ac9c756" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"46a0b6ed903b">Approximate (structural)</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"5a8f41c4-e5d8-4995-adb1-8f58a2b62e46" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"ddfb12f1d69a">Low</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"68cf12f1-194c-4e68-8815-e84f15441ef5">
<td data-local-id=3D"e8c69840-429f-46a3-901d-484b96e5560b" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"5fc310ce5704">Coverage</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"4f091247-c583-46dd-909a-a9d13f9ddab0" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"7878a1b976e8">CI coverage report ingestion</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"283751db-2c68-401d-bc05-359d50c1664d" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"5188314afa99">After CI completion</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"7fe837cd-9cd2-48e5-a9ea-252a1d7d6d19" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"e82709475102">Precise (execution-verified)</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"55a9068c-e798-48d5-bbcd-af5555f79d8a" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"4c606e0026e3">Low (ingestion only)</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p local-id=3D"6223c50a72ca">The static layer provides a fast, cheap, alway=
s-on baseline. The coverage layer provides ground truth when available. Que=
ries should use coverage data when present and fall back to static linkage =
otherwise.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"1754b110fa0f" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.2CoverageReportFormats">3.2 Coverage Report Formats</h3>
<p local-id=3D"bae65120cf05">Coverage formats (LCOV, JaCoCo, Cobertura) are=
 standardized output formats, not testing frameworks. Testing frameworks (J=
est, Vitest, pytest, cargo test, etc.) produce test results. Coverage tools=
 (Istanbul/nyc, JaCoCo, llvm-cov/tarpaulin, coverage.py) instrument code an=
d produce reports in these standard formats.</p>
<p local-id=3D"57dcc4a83e9d">This means integration effort targets a small =
number of report parsers rather than every testing framework individually.<=
/p>
<p local-id=3D"fb3eaaf419b7"><strong>MVP decision: LCOV as the single cover=
age format.</strong></p>
<ul local-id=3D"d17bc7ed-96c3-477d-a17f-a98965486ac2">
<li local-id=3D"832fc07a-ecf9-4165-9408-d3003f5bba4d">
<p local-id=3D"870b1059ac81">For TypeScript: Istanbul/nyc produces LCOV (Je=
st and Vitest both support this natively).</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"1f95f16a-9f10-42d6-bdb1-ad1f4311d133">
<p local-id=3D"b48a3eb0db91">For Rust: cargo-tarpaulin or llvm-cov, also pr=
oducing LCOV.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"b77504e0-bd01-4cc0-88c6-54a5283e1d8a">
<p local-id=3D"caaded281818">A single LCOV parser is sufficient for both MV=
P target languages.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"e79d0cb0706a">For future expansion, 3=E2=80=934 parsers tota=
l (LCOV, JaCoCo, Cobertura) would cover JS/TS, Rust, C/C++, JVM, Python, an=
d .NET ecosystems.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"55a947ca34f7" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.3TestClassification">3.3 Test Classification</h3>
<h4 local-id=3D"e270d7c91494" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Theclassificationlandscape">The classification landscape</h4>
<p local-id=3D"ffbb26df64f2">The testing world recognises many test types: =
unit, integration, functional, end-to-end, acceptance, performance, smoke, =
and others. These differ along two axes:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"4dbe4cd4-33cd-4003-bc4e-51f0b2edc4c5">
<li local-id=3D"afd9d2aa-6247-47a3-b9f8-11dd239ca62e">
<p local-id=3D"f19b4943562d"><strong>Coverage shape</strong> =E2=80=94 what=
 the test touches in the codebase (fan-out, boundary crossing, depth).</p><=
/li>
<li local-id=3D"fe89aa12-f238-452b-b2fa-c48fe4215a92">
<p local-id=3D"57511d9834ed"><strong>Purpose/intent</strong> =E2=80=94 why =
the test exists (verifying a unit of logic, checking business requirements,=
 measuring performance).</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"898fb977c8ac">Coverage-derived classification can only see t=
he first axis. The distinction between types that share similar coverage sh=
apes but differ in intent requires human-provided metadata or inference:</p=
>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"a0=
1c7efe-d996-4420-ac91-9c85aa8a20af" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr data-local-id=3D"9147231e-d46c-4e52-8f0a-dcedbac406d0">
<th data-local-id=3D"cb188804-fc7e-414d-925d-af12dd26feb5" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"cdf49acc9474"><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=
=3D"b3c8a315-3e21-4bc9-9ade-880354344c07">Test type</span></p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"9c2fe1e1-d650-4ec0-af1a-8f510ebb1b17" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"2d9c7be4fe74">Coverage shape</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"c4aac708-a2b4-4ab2-ac98-b4db7041ab50" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"975c1757758d">Distinguishing factor</p></th>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"f9fca0da-a8eb-4d14-8192-deb151d80fe5">
<td data-local-id=3D"f2d518b4-c33d-4b59-a09a-d4882f16103d" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"66953f0f32d4"><strong>Unit</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"695ba258-ed1b-49bc-b305-470f479ed905" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"7d80c72f8e56">Low fan-out, single artefact, no external boun=
daries crossed</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"169ba7b4-ee7e-4994-a1fd-2fc8817ca4a9" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"86f108a70be0">Coverage shape =E2=80=94 detectable</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"19a64e0e-a208-493a-9161-44e969762fcd">
<td data-local-id=3D"c09b2663-8682-40b5-9355-e2d0eeb387ba" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"704a4c491b25"><strong>Integration</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"db9c80ce-66a6-4dd2-91fe-270fc6d9a8e2" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"0fb4901b3778">Moderate fan-out, multiple artefacts, <span cl=
ass=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=3D"f4c98175-d83a-48a2-9e45-111ace490=
3b4">crosses module boundaries</span></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"9a79a4ba-0a6d-44f9-ad1b-9e6c762e14d1" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"e421f5c0e1f9">Coverage shape =E2=80=94 detectable</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"104fa6e0-f7ba-4c6d-80b9-77e538ed1463">
<td data-local-id=3D"1ed418e3-4e8e-4fd1-8f87-2750e19d46a5" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"6a42509c82d7"><strong>Functional</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"43627e89-57f2-49e6-9275-91f27dd745f7" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"b2377b6aae62">Similar to integration =E2=80=94 touches multi=
ple components</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"64b3e385-f6e3-441e-85a0-1c482fa97375" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"c3f2df4c73f4">Purpose (business requirements vs component in=
teraction) =E2=80=94 not detectable from coverage</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"51d97a43-582e-486d-8af2-569ae466eedc">
<td data-local-id=3D"56f96bb0-ca2d-43d7-abe9-5f856d3499a9" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"cd05eb381853"><strong>End-to-end</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"72245014-fe69-45ab-9d48-f529599b0445" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"0fcba1f0b0e9">High fan-out, crosses service boundaries, touc=
hes many layers</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"7009eb82-27b7-49fc-8a4e-c3b0cc052e1c" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"d1eb45d46845">Coverage shape =E2=80=94 detectable</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"7125bf16-2e84-44dc-87a7-94007d64045c">
<td data-local-id=3D"cb7cb47c-1a8d-4ccf-9223-3e07be06d3bd" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"59c7b406c08b"><strong>Acceptance</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"81a8112f-2afb-427a-b5fa-72badfb0c43c" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"b5e5cf9b9459">Similar to e2e =E2=80=94 broad coverage footpr=
int</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"d5869400-2ce2-4f7a-9a6b-60392ec52339" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"4fead486a0a2">Purpose (business requirements validation) =E2=
=80=94 not detectable from coverage</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"7d3888b9-d17f-4d91-8d57-5bd653ac5740">
<td data-local-id=3D"76fa7bf0-03b5-4744-b100-4815025e06b1" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"112248bf4dd1"><strong>Smoke</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"e721ec2f-8bc8-419f-96a7-9b7151b9a91d" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"3e1c7f1c1832"><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=
=3D"1ac8c5f1-6bb8-448f-89aa-6bb8f8a3603d">Varies =E2=80=94 could look like =
unit (narrow) or e2e (broad surface)</span></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"b6d00758-b117-4fd0-ae94-f957a586980c" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"00326e19a35f">Purpose (quick sanity check) =E2=80=94 not det=
ectable from coverage</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"1c02e6e8-901f-4881-89f0-57b47cf47629">
<td data-local-id=3D"0b74e394-361f-40e8-b2b6-2056a25ac59c" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"65c170f24b5d"><strong>Performance</strong></p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"0faab36c-45fa-47be-804b-a0fabca2abb4" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"8133105ed2c5">Not a functional test at all</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"3c245e3b-2473-4cb5-8db2-edae3cb95753" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"507e5db9d808">Different ingestion path entirely =E2=80=94 ou=
t of scope for coverage-derived classification</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<h4 local-id=3D"722e29d188c0" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Primarymethod(MVP):Coverage-derivedclassification">Primary method (MVP=
): Coverage-derived classification</h4>
<p local-id=3D"b24b0e021d39">Zero user configuration. Classification is inf=
erred as a derived property from the coverage footprint =E2=80=94 specifica=
lly artefact fan-out and service/module boundary crossing:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"2fbf12de-4ae5-4983-9080-a2afb60281d2">
<li local-id=3D"0601e2c2-6525-492d-9d40-377cc27fd402">
<p local-id=3D"78e3e0651bae">A test covering a single artefact in a single =
file behaves like a <strong>unit test</strong>.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"5a05d172-0a40-47a9-949d-32c71be44e02">
<p local-id=3D"c98c80037d75">A test touching multiple artefacts across seve=
ral modules behaves like an <strong>integration test</strong>.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"5b96265b-0708-4b11-b7c7-f7b29e47927b">
<p local-id=3D"fb4e2ffbafce">A test spanning many artefacts across service =
boundaries behaves like an <strong>e2e test</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p local-id=3D"2e4c305bd1d1">This three-tier model (unit / integration / e2=
e) captures what coverage data can actually tell us. It is framework-agnost=
ic, language-agnostic, and based on actual behaviour rather than naming con=
ventions.</p>
<h4 local-id=3D"b615e1a795f0" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Secondarymethod(optionaloverride):Convention-basedclassification">Seco=
ndary method (optional override): Convention-based classification</h4>
<p local-id=3D"508bf7525fdf">Users who want explicit control can configure =
folder/file naming patterns (e.g., <code>__tests__/unit/</code>, <code>*.in=
tegration.test.ts</code>). This overrides the coverage-derived classificati=
on for matching tests.</p>
<p local-id=3D"b4cd4cc97d61">The classification enum is <strong>open and ex=
tensible</strong>. The coverage-derived engine outputs <code>unit</code>, <=
code>integration</code>, or <code>e2e</code>. But convention-based override=
s can use any label the user defines =E2=80=94 including <code>functional</=
code>, <code>smoke</code>, <code>acceptance</code>, <code>performance</code=
>, or custom types specific to their project. This preserves the zero-frict=
ion default while allowing teams with richer test taxonomies to express the=
m.</p>
<p local-id=3D"5eb7f7143d6a">The ordering is deliberate: coverage-derived f=
irst means the system works out of the box with no setup. Convention-based =
is available for users who have strong opinions about their test taxonomy, =
who need finer-grained distinctions (e.g., functional vs integration), or w=
ho want to correct misclassifications.</p>
<h4 local-id=3D"416ed6b7d738" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Discardedoptions">Discarded options</h4>
<ul local-id=3D"effed6a2-a589-45b0-96db-fb2c50649be9">
<li local-id=3D"fb3acf5d-33d9-497d-a57d-b1752f8eab0e">
<p local-id=3D"d90eb309841d"><em>Heuristic/rule-based</em> (mock detection =
per framework): Painful to maintain across frameworks. Deferred =E2=80=94 m=
ay revisit for high-confidence patterns in supported languages (e.g., <code=
>jest.mock</code>, <code>vi.mock</code> for TS; <code>#[mockall]</code> for=
 Rust).</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"1a6d004d-98cd-43cd-8070-8cf6daf09591">
<p local-id=3D"0c643d9277f6"><em>LLM inference</em>: Overkill for classific=
ation when simpler signals exist. Not worth the cost and latency.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 local-id=3D"9906f02094fe" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.4TargetLanguages(MVP)">3.4 Target Languages (MVP)</h3>
<p local-id=3D"4d794f64ccc6">TypeScript and Rust. Different enough to valid=
ate that the model generalizes, both with strong tooling ecosystems.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"28aa16a6ed9b" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.5Commit-AddressableStorage">3.5 Commit-Addressable Storage</h3>
<p local-id=3D"545bfa809659">Per the platform-wide data architecture princi=
ples (<a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://claude.ai/chat/fe5670fd-a3=
ff-4833-8b59-065a0e091e88#appendix-a-commit-addressable-storage-explained" =
rel=3D"nofollow">Why-see Appendix?</a>):</p>
<ul local-id=3D"43a72ebc-bb09-4225-9173-58608bf31ca1">
<li local-id=3D"3b66c709-a8c2-4f0b-80ea-14d312868a0a">
<p local-id=3D"fa8a32ed66ce">All derived intelligence is stored against imm=
utable <code>commit_sha</code> snapshots.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"7ca0063d-2751-4526-a167-4ebaf78eeac4">
<p local-id=3D"9f7eb8791b62">Branches/tags (refs) resolve to commits at que=
ry time.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"7b5feb5a-c346-4a4b-b24b-e7fbeaf67975">
<p local-id=3D"59ba942510bf">Historical ref movement is preserved for as-of=
 reproducibility.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"ef927e52-e9d8-4c4b-a000-41f4b2f35862">
<p local-id=3D"613c642eb91d">No branch-only facts without commit linkage.</=
p></li>
</ul>
<h3 local-id=3D"db1305f3c11c" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.6PrimaryConsumer:LLMAgents">3.6 Primary Consumer: LLM Agents</h3>
<p local-id=3D"9b9b320b68eb">The primary consumer of <code>getTestHarness</=
code> is an LLM agent executing a coding task (e.g., refactoring, adding fe=
atures, fixing bugs). The developer is a secondary consumer.</p>
<p local-id=3D"50f91cb626cc">The typical agent workflow is:</p>
<ol start=3D"1" local-id=3D"b11414d5-b82e-4b83-a355-f5ee74454b60">
<li local-id=3D"584cb5ea-1ec2-4e00-9ef0-f57ab93f8322">
<p local-id=3D"6ea2a7a1d090">Agent receives a task involving an artefact.</=
p></li>
<li local-id=3D"e0785eb1-220a-4506-bc88-0b13e9e9b34f">
<p local-id=3D"09943eca8184"><strong>Before making any change</strong>, age=
nt queries <code>getTestHarness</code> against the current committed state =
to understand the verification landscape: what tests exist, what's covered,=
 what's not.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"085f3e43-d860-43f3-b1cb-5f2c1dc82d12">
<p local-id=3D"e9ca52e999ed">Agent uses this context to inform its change =
=E2=80=94 avoiding breaking existing tests, identifying untested paths, dec=
iding whether to write new tests.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"15f52cad-51ce-438b-a707-94d0e77c6cf8">
<p local-id=3D"e2cf8ead3042">Agent makes the change and commits.</p></li>
</ol>
<p local-id=3D"5af2a0d43b86">This means the committed state is the primary =
query target. It represents the pre-change baseline, which is exactly what =
the agent needs at planning time.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"3285f1277128" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.7CoverageGeneration:LocalCLI">3.7 Coverage Generation: Local CLI</h3=
>
<p local-id=3D"302461473569">Coverage data is not generated by a remote CI =
server. The platform is a CLI tool that triggers test runs locally (or via =
commit hooks), collects LCOV output, and ingests it. This means:</p>
<ul local-id=3D"428422b2-8d71-4413-9d6d-9ee557d88653">
<li local-id=3D"ea0e9a53-0492-4ea3-94f4-af17c5469400">
<p local-id=3D"2d83a94d3849">Coverage data can be generated frequently and =
with low latency.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"13e1f8fe-2e90-4d0c-8690-54edbcaf98ef">
<p local-id=3D"757ed1194f6f">An agent or developer can trigger a test run, =
get fresh coverage, and ingest it =E2=80=94 all locally, within seconds dep=
ending on suite size.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"840585f8-13c0-4c56-8f45-639198ba06ec">
<p local-id=3D"89573c7fd081">The committed state will typically have recent=
, relevant coverage data available.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 local-id=3D"cf23df9aa9a1" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.8UncommittedWorkspaceState(Deferred)">3.8 Uncommitted Workspace Stat=
e (Deferred)</h3>
<p local-id=3D"5bf0c2c174a0">For MVP, <code>getTestHarness</code> queries a=
gainst committed state only. Uncommitted workspace linkage is a secondary s=
cenario (e.g., an agent reassessing after making changes but before committ=
ing) and is deferred. The static linkage layer <em>could</em> operate on wo=
rkspace snapshots since Tree-sitter can parse uncommitted files, but covera=
ge data is inherently tied to committed, test-executed code. Mixing stale c=
overage with fresh static linkage adds complexity without clear value for t=
he primary agent workflow.</p>
<h3 local-id=3D"2bedff3de360" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-3.9TestTypeAffectsSignalStrength">3.9 Test Type Affects Signal Strengt=
h</h3>
<p local-id=3D"8a024eeb8d48">Unit tests with a clean 1-to-1 mapping to an a=
rtefact are a stronger coverage signal than an e2e test that happens to tou=
ch the same artefact among dozens of others. The coverage data captures thi=
s naturally (it reports all lines hit), but the <em>usefulness</em> of that=
 linkage varies. The model captures test type as metadata on the test-to-ar=
tefact relationship, enabling consumers to weight coverage signals appropri=
ately.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"aa3199a1-be10-43ce-ab07-42b2a394e939">
<h2 local-id=3D"ed0ee6e4236f" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-4.QueryInterface&amp;ResponseShape">4. Query Interface &amp; Response =
Shape</h2>
<h3 local-id=3D"38ea45a98e68" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-4.1DevQLIntegration">4.1 DevQL Integration</h3>
<p local-id=3D"dcab78c2d3de"><code>getTestHarness</code> is not an isolated=
 function call. It is accessed through DevQL =E2=80=94 the platform's graph=
-navigation query language. Test harness data is reached by traversing the =
repository graph to an artefact and then resolving its test relationships.<=
/p>
<h4 local-id=3D"17b8dc871900" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-NewDevQLPrimitives">New DevQL Primitives</h4>
<p local-id=3D"b12a2eadaf22"><code>tests()</code> =E2=80=94 Resolves the te=
st harness for artefacts in the current result set. Returns covering tests =
with classification, confidence, strength, and last run status.</p>
<p local-id=3D"0abc7379ac8f"><code>coverage()</code> =E2=80=94 Returns deta=
iled coverage data (line, branch, per-branch status) for the current artefa=
ct or test context.</p>
<h4 local-id=3D"6678de002f98" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-ExampleQueries">Example Queries</h4>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">// Full=
 test harness for an artefact
repo("repo1")
  -&gt; asOf(ref:"main")
  -&gt; file("src/users/UserRepository.ts")
  -&gt; artefacts(name:"findById")
  -&gt; tests()

// Filter to unit tests only
repo("repo1")
  -&gt; asOf(ref:"main")
  -&gt; file("src/users/UserRepository.ts")
  -&gt; artefacts(name:"findById")
  -&gt; tests(classification:"unit")

// Get detailed coverage for an artefact
repo("repo1")
  -&gt; asOf(ref:"main")
  -&gt; file("src/users/UserRepository.ts")
  -&gt; artefacts(name:"findById")
  -&gt; coverage()

// Compose with other capabilities
repo("repo1")
  -&gt; asOf(ref:"main")
  -&gt; file("src/users/UserRepository.ts")
  -&gt; artefacts(name:"findById")
  -&gt; tests()
  -&gt; blastRadius()</pre>
</div>
</div>
<h4 local-id=3D"21d4932e40b9" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-StoreResolution">Store Resolution</h4>
<p local-id=3D"e3c59d4adb57">The DevQL resolver for <code>tests()</code> an=
d <code>coverage()</code> fans out across stores as needed:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"41=
b4833b-b254-4140-8627-a6caa768fe19" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr data-local-id=3D"16fef378-5a2e-4670-94d8-b527af79e905">
<th data-local-id=3D"c90b8027-2e07-4f4c-aaab-40d2b91d0da4" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"8385376fbcff">Data</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"95959f21-9a2b-45c4-a7a3-e668b92d64c2" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"574a34768ef5">Store</p></th>
<th data-local-id=3D"e8663827-ca68-4134-84ad-b80f1fcadbaf" class=3D"conflue=
nceTh">
<p local-id=3D"3fecc95150fc">Rationale</p></th>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"4a46b4d3-2e5c-41dc-869a-728711a9cb5b">
<td data-local-id=3D"000124db-c8f7-41ac-ab4b-a1d8af3f4c3b" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"b0dacbc1d36e">Test artefacts (suites, scenarios)</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"7198d6e2-dad1-4fa6-b2cb-8791e8efeb86" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"388352a7d787">PostgreSQL</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"73798536-ef8f-4265-98fa-0875154be233" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"e4132713a3c9">Structural, relational, commit-addressable</p>=
</td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"81641c90-0c94-415c-b84a-a50fc300d8a0">
<td data-local-id=3D"c3c2f8ae-1a6b-4c4c-8a93-0910d63dadbf" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"93da655007f8">Static linkage (test =E2=86=92 production arte=
fact)</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"4ac74a9b-e874-42b1-b265-7fd5e471adc3" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"8f3633f4c320">PostgreSQL</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"070e7a15-9fbf-4615-a39d-2c23a0e3b2d0" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"9532e8116b24">Relational edges</p></td>
</tr>
<tr data-local-id=3D"1c957c3a-12f9-4d33-856c-4c9aee472ea4">
<td data-local-id=3D"f648edb6-0091-43bb-aa06-666b2a1bd363" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"2cbc18b160ea">Coverage data (branch/line per artefact)</p></=
td>
<td data-local-id=3D"76bd431a-a66e-440b-b534-21f7a3254b63" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
<p local-id=3D"52723efdcf02">PostgreSQL</p></td>
<td data-local-id=3D"74203fbf-a721-44f4-b287-24429f580b5b" class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">
