<h3 local-id=3D"a9977378fcfa" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-Knowngapstovalidate">Known gaps to validate</h3>
<ul local-id=3D"92c3e87a-855d-4307-aa2e-847deb65a5cd">
<li local-id=3D"5e93a6a5-1850-4c07-a143-69ae6d5c2a38">
<p local-id=3D"bd8da699fd6d"><strong>Rust support:</strong> Nomic Embed Cod=
e lists Python, Java, Ruby, PHP, JavaScript, Go =E2=80=94 no explicit Rust =
support. Qodo lists TypeScript explicitly but Rust coverage is unclear. Bot=
h need validation on actual Rust code before committing.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"6c704c89-20f4-4654-a113-723bbeec7810">
<p local-id=3D"b37e61d3ee7e"><strong>TypeScript vs JavaScript:</strong> Jav=
aScript support doesn't guarantee TypeScript-specific understanding (type a=
nnotations, generics, interfaces). Needs testing.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"86667e53-db7f-4e92-be9e-c995b48b9ae6">
<p local-id=3D"97444924e9b3"><strong>Test code specifically:</strong> These=
 models are benchmarked on general code retrieval. Performance on test-spec=
ific patterns (fixtures, mocks, assertion structures) is unvalidated. May b=
enefit from fine-tuning on test corpora.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"537e3065-762d-4cb3-94e3-2608994f11de">
<p local-id=3D"f2a5307e578d"><strong>Benchmark reliability:</strong> MTEB s=
cores are self-reported. CoIR is more rigorous but still synthetic. Always =
validate on your own data.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr local-id=3D"f70822f8-627c-4f9e-a2df-64da86f90d6e">
<h2 local-id=3D"438127718c67" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-6.Dependencies">6. Dependencies</h2>
<ul local-id=3D"c4372471-2418-44b1-ae0d-cee265874888">
<li local-id=3D"b86d2783-7383-4584-863f-79d10f495af9">
<p local-id=3D"6620bd97b67a"><strong>From </strong><code>getBlastRadius</co=
de><strong> / Static Analysis Layer:</strong> Tree-sitter parsing infrastru=
cture, artefact model with file path + line span mappings, dependency graph=
.</p></li>
<li local-id=3D"0966aae8-5489-4462-bfa5-429dd703adc4">
<p local-id=3D"9ee7c38f29a3"><strong>From CI/CD integration:</strong> Abili=
ty to ingest LCOV coverage reports and test run outcomes per commit.</p></l=
i>
<li local-id=3D"1e4f7863-2313-4455-a39e-3aa8da2a4b04">
<p local-id=3D"fade3003fe28"><strong>From Temporal Model:</strong> Commit-a=
ddressable storage, ref resolution, workspace snapshot support.<br></p></li=
>
</ul>
<hr local-id=3D"06367009-6846-4fab-8b6d-e6648a93ab00">
<hr local-id=3D"bfde7fae-eaac-4d59-b48b-606766f2aa77">
<h2 local-id=3D"f6bd55867d22" id=3D"TestHarness-DesignSpecification(Fullvis=
ion)-7.Glossary">7. Glossary</h2>
<blockquote local-id=3D"04ce8d36-c0d7-4b16-9333-7ff38b34f49c">
<p local-id=3D"88a00a2d8b85">Terms defined in the platform-wide glossary (A=
rtefact, Ref, Snapshot, Confidence Score, etc.) are not repeated here. The =
following are specific to <code>getTestHarness</code>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p local-id=3D"9cdc515142db"><strong>Branch coverage</strong> =E2=80=94 The=
 percentage of conditional branches (if/else, match arms, ternary expressio=
ns, guard clauses) exercised by tests. A function with an if/else has two b=
ranches; 100% branch coverage means both paths were executed. More precise =
than line coverage, since a single line can contain multiple branches.</p>
<p local-id=3D"cea3cbef4ef5"><strong>Line coverage</strong> =E2=80=94 The p=
ercentage of executable lines in a source file or artefact that were hit du=
ring test execution. The most common and coarsest coverage metric.</p>
<p local-id=3D"06e69c94cf91"><strong>Path coverage</strong> =E2=80=94 The p=
ercentage of distinct execution paths through a function or artefact exerci=
sed by tests. More granular than branch coverage, since it considers combin=
ations of branches (e.g., a function with two independent if/else blocks ha=
s four paths but only four branches).</p>
<p local-id=3D"8de28bf877e4"><strong>Fan-out</strong> =E2=80=94 The number =
of distinct production artefacts a single test touches during execution. Us=
ed as the primary signal for coverage-derived test classification: low fan-=
out suggests a unit test, high fan-out suggests integration or e2e.</p>
<p local-id=3D"006c1923b1bb"><strong>Test suite</strong> =E2=80=94 A groupi=
ng of related test scenarios. Corresponds to a <code>describe</code> block =
in Jest/Vitest, a <code>mod tests</code> in Rust, or equivalent constructs =
in other frameworks. Represented as a first-class artefact in the test doma=
in.</p>
<p local-id=3D"ce0fb047d936"><strong>Test scenario</strong> =E2=80=94 An in=
dividual test case. Corresponds to an <code>it</code>/<code>test</code> blo=
ck in Jest/Vitest, a <code>#[test]</code> function in Rust, or equivalent. =
The atomic unit to which coverage data, run outcomes, and classification me=
tadata attach.</p>
    </div>
</body>
